04594nam a22005535i 9781554581665DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815545816657 a10.51644/97815545816652doi  a(DE-B1597)667494  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9188.2.M55bK35 2009eb 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04aC810.9/81 aKamboureli, Smaro, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScandalous Bodies :bDiasporic Literature in English Canada /cSmaro Kamboureli. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransCanada00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- tCritical Correspondences: the Diasporic Critic’s (Self-)Location -- tRealism and the History of Reality: F.P. Grove’s Settlers of the Marsh -- tSedative Politics: Media, Law, Philosophy -- tEthnic Anthologies: From Designated Margins to Postmodern Multiculturalism -- tThe Body in Joy Kogawa’s Obasan: Race, Gender, Sexuality -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tBooks in the TransCanada Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aScandalous Bodies is an impassioned scholarly study both of literature by diasporic writers and of the contexts within which it is produced. It explores topics ranging from the Canadian government’s multiculturalism policy to media representations of so-called minority groups, from the relationship between realist fiction and history to postmodern constructions of ethnicity, from the multicultural theory of the philosopher Charles Taylor to the cultural responsibilities of diasporic critics such as Kamboureli herself. Smaro Kamboureli proposes no neat or comforting solutions to the problems she addresses. Rather than adhere to a single method of reading or make her argument follow a systematic approach, she lets the texts and the socio-cultural contexts she examines give shape to her reading. In fact, methodological issues, and the need to revisit them, become a leitmotif in the book. Theoretically rigorous and historically situated, this study also engages with close reading—not the kind that views a text as a sovereign world, but one that opens the text in order to reveal the method of its making. Her practice of what she calls negative pedagogy—a self-reflexive method of learning and unlearning, of decoding the means through which knowledge is produced—allows her to avoid the pitfalls of constructing a narrative of progress. Her critique of Canadian multiculturalism as a policy that advocates what she calls “sedative politics” and of the epistemologies of ethnicity that have shaped, for example, the first wave of ethnic anthologies in Canada are the backdrop against which she examines the various discourses that inform the diasporic experience in Canada. Scandalous Bodies was first published in 2000 and received the Gabrielle Roy Prize for Canadian Criticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literaturexMinority authorsxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 4aSocial Science: Multiculturalism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458166540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554581665423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554581665/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Packa